<HEADLINE>
KAOHSIUNG UNIVERSITY HOLDS INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE ON
TRANSLATION
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kaohsiung   County,  April   27  (CNA) 04/27/07  21:44:07 (By Han
Nai-kuo)
</P>
<P>
The 2007  International Conference on Translation and
Interpretation, organized by the Department of English of
National Kaohsiung First University of Science and Technology,
took place Friday, with some 300 people taking part.
</P>
<P>
Discussions  at the conference  centered around the theme,
"Translation and Interpretation -- Theory, Teaching and
Practice."
</P>
<P>
The one-day conference presented five speeches by professors from
Taiwan and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Robin Setton, a professor of the University of Geneva who has
done extensive research on interpretation and translation, gave
two speeches at the conference.
</P>
<P>
He spoke on "Understanding Interpreting in Terms of a General
Theory of Communication"  and later on "Interpreter  Training:
Unavoidable Universals vs. Possible Local Adaptations."
</P>
<P>
Father Daniel Bauer, associate professor of English language and
literature at Fu Jen Catholic University in Taipei County, spoke
on "Cross-Cultural Problems in Short Translations of Literature,"
using works by Taiwanese writers Ping Lu and Tien Hsin-bin as
examples.
</P>
<P>
Paul Cox, a lecturer at Fu Jen Catholic University's Graduate
Institute of Translation and Interpretation Studies, gave a
speech on "Fundamentals of Legal Translation for Instructors and
Practioners," while Chen Pi-chu, a lecturer at National Taiwan
Normal University's Graduate Institute of Translation and
Interpretation, presented a paper on "The Task of the Translation
Editor."
</P>
